{{otheruses}}
[[File:Um yeah, hooray for slow dancing!! (1382786008).jpg|thumb|People slow dancing at a wedding]] A '''slow dance''' is a type of [[partner dance]] in which a couple [[dance]] slowly, swaying to the [[music]]. This is usually done to very slow-beat [[song]]s, namely [[sentimental ballads]]. This simple form of slow dancing is common at dances sponsored by schools or by religious organizations, such as churches or synagogues. In Western popular culture, slow dancing can serve as a symbol of [[adolescence|adolescent]] social awkwardness.<ref name=Mansour2005 />
Slow dancing can refer to any slow couple dance (such as certain [[ballroom dance]]s), but is often associated with a particular, simple style of dance performed by [[middle school]], [[high school]] and [[college]] students.<ref name=Mansour2005>{{cite book|last=Mansour|first=David|title=From Abba to Zoom: A Pop Culture Encyclopedia of the Late 20th Century|publisher=Andrews McMeel Publishing|date=2005|page=445|isbn=978-0-7407-5118-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b1ruwF6xYNIC&pg=PA445&dq=%22slow+dance%22&lr=&as_brr=3&as_pt=ALLTYPES}}</ref>
==Technique== When two partners dance together, the lead partner- usually male- typically holds their hands against the sides of the following - usually female- partner's [[hip]]s, [[buttocks]] or [[waist]] while the follower drapes their hands on the leader's shoulders. The couple then sways back and forth with the music. Foot movement is minimal, but the pair may use their feet to slowly turn on the spot. Because the dance requires little physical concentration, participants often talk to each other while dancing. Some couples who have a close relationship may dance very closely together, in a "hug-and-sway" fashion.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pruter|first=Robert|title=Chicago Soul|publisher=University of Illinois Press|date=1992|page=207|isbn=978-0-252-06259-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2kkcmS0AzMEC&pg=PA207&dq=%22slow+dance%22&lr=&as_brr=3&as_pt=ALLTYPES}}</ref>
