{{good article}} {{Infobox film | name = Wanita dan Satria | image = Wanita dan Satria cover.jpg | image_size = | border = | alt = | caption = Cover of the novelisation | director = [[Rd Ariffien]] | producer =Ang Hock Liem | screenplay = | narrator = | starring ={{plain list| *[[Djoewariah]] *Ratna Djoewita *Hidajat }} | music = | cinematography = | editing = | studio = [[Union Films]] | distributor = | released = {{Film date|df=yes|1941|||Dutch East Indies}} | runtime = | country = [[Dutch East Indies]] | language = Indonesian | budget = | gross = }} '''''Wanita dan Satria''''' ({{IPA-id|waˈnita ˈdan satˈria|}}; Indonesian for ''The Woman and the Hero'') is a 1941 film from the [[Dutch East Indies]] (now Indonesia) directed by [[Rd Ariffien]] and produced by Ang Hock Liem for [[Union Films]] that is probably [[lost film|lost]]. Starring [[Djoewariah]], Ratna Djoewita, Hidajat, Z. Algadrie, and Moesa, it follows a womaniser named Soedrajat who abuses his status to gain women's trust before ultimately getting his comeuppance. Reviews were mostly positive, with one praising the film's depiction of [[Women in Indonesia|women's issues]] in a Muslim society.
==Plot== Soedrajat abuses his high social status in order to womanise and becomes his rich uncle's heir despite the latter having a son, the kindly and noble Soelarsa. The uncle is disappointed with Soelarsa and considers Soedrajat the better man. Being considered high class, he is unwilling to associate with people of the lower classes. Ultimately Soedrajat falls for a beautiful young woman, Koestijah. Meanwhile, Soelarsa saves Koestijah's life while driving a truck through her village; the two fall in love at first sight. By manipulating Koestijah's father, Soedrajat arranges for her to marry him.
At the wedding, however, the terrible truth about Soedrajat is revealed. One of his former conquests, Tarmini, stands up and tells the crowd, including Soelarsa, of the bridegroom's true nature. In a rage, Soedrajat takes a revolver and shoots Tarmini. With her dying breath, Tarmini makes one last confession. Her father then takes revenge on Soedrajat.{{efn|Film plot derived from two contemporary newspaper reviews. See {{harvnb|Soerabaijasch Handelsblad 1941, Sampoerna a}} and {{harvnb|Soerabaijasch Handelsblad 1941, Sampoerna b}}.}}
==Production== ''Wanita dan Satria'' was produced by Ang Hock Liem for [[Union Films]]. It was directed by [[Rd Ariffien]], a former theatre leader and nationalist journalist who had made his directorial debut the preceding year with ''[[Harta Berdarah]]''.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Wanita dan Satria}}; {{harvnb|Biran|2009|p=233}}.</ref> The story was written by [[Saeroen]], a former journalist with several screenwriting credits for Union.{{sfn|Soerabaijasch Handelsblad 1941, Sampoerna a}}
The [[black-and-white]] film starred [[Djoewariah]], Ratna Djoewita, Hidajat, Z. Algadrie, and Moesa.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Wanita dan Satria}}; {{harvnb|Soerabaijasch Handelsblad 1941, (untitled)}}</ref> Moesa was the most experienced of these: he had entered the industry in 1938 with ''[[Fatima (1938 film)|Fatima]]'', a production by [[Tan's Film]], and had been with Union since 1940.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Moesa}} Djoewariah had been on Union's payroll since ''[[Bajar dengan Djiwa]]'' in 1940,{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djuariah}} while Ratna Djoewita and Hidajat had not appeared in any films before 1941.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Ratna Djoewita}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, R Hidajat}}.</ref>
==Release and reception== ''Wanita dan Satria'' was released in 1941, reaching [[Bandung]] by August{{sfn|Bataviaasch Nieuwsblad 1941, Bandoeng}} and [[Surabaya]] by September. The film was open to all ages.{{sfn|Soerabaijasch Handelsblad 1941, (untitled)}} A novelisation was published later in 1941 by the [[Yogyakarta]]-based Kolff-Buning.{{sfn|WorldCat, Wanita dan Satria}} As part of the growing movement to attract Indonesian intellectuals, the marketing staff emphasised the respectable (non-theatrical) background of the actors; the intelligentsia had little respect for traditional theatre and its players.{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=262–263}}
A review in the Surabaya-based ''[[Soerabaijasch Handelsblad]]'' wrote that the film "gives a clear picture of the precarious position of Indonesian women and motivates the desire for a firmer outline of her rights in the Moslem society."{{efn|Original: "... ''geeft een duidelijk beeld van de wankele positie der Indonesische vrouw en motiveert den drang naar een vaster omlijning harer rechten In de Mohammedaansche maatschappij.''"}}{{sfn|Soerabaijasch Handelsblad 1941, Sampoerna a}} Another review in the same newspaper wrote that the film "is captivating from start to finish",{{efn|Original: "... ''is van het begin tot het eind boeiend.''"}} one which "the film audience in Surabaya should certainly not miss".{{efn|Original: "... ''het Soerabaiasche filmpubliek beslist niet missen.''"}}{{sfn|Soerabaijasch Handelsblad 1941, Sampoerna b}}
==Legacy== After ''Wanita dan Satria'', Union produced a further two films;{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=233}} none of these were by Rd. Ariffien, who had left the company.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=263}} Saeroen likewise left soon after, joining [[Star Film (Dutch East Indies company)|Star Film]].{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=234}} Djoewariah continued to act until the 1950s, when she migrated to theatre after receiving a series of increasingly minor roles.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djuariah}} Neither Ratna Djoewita nor Hidajat appeared in any films after 1941.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Ratna Djoewita}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, R Hidajat}}.</ref>
The film is likely [[lost film|lost]]; the American visual anthropologist [[Karl G. Heider]] writes that all Indonesian films from before 1950 are lost.{{sfn|Heider|1991|p=14}} However, JB Kristanto's ''Katalog Film Indonesia'' (''Indonesian Film Catalogue'') records several as having survived at [[Sinematek Indonesia]]'s archives, and Biran writes that several Japanese propaganda films have survived at the [[Netherlands Government Information Service]].{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=351}}
